{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646801"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:35:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:35:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18209"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18209"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.05,0.11,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73823"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10923"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59299"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5292"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"9982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25393"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73823"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effects of TNF alpha antagonists on joint health?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase collagen synthesis in joints","Promote synovial fluid production","Stimulate bone resorption","Enhance the activity of metalloproteinases","Reduce inflammation and slow joint damage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETNF alpha antagonists work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ereducing inflammation and slowing joint damage\u003C/strong\u003E. These drugs inhibit the action of TNF alpha, a cytokine that contributes to inflammation and the breakdown of collagen in joints. By blocking TNF alpha, these medications help maintain the integrity of affected joints and slow the progression of diseases like rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease collagen synthesis in joints\u003C/strong\u003E - While TNF alpha antagonists reduce collagen breakdown, they do not directly increase collagen synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhance the activity of metalloproteinases\u003C/strong\u003E - These drugs inhibit TNF alpha, which reduces metalloproteinase activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulate bone resorption\u003C/strong\u003E - TNF alpha antagonists do not promote bone resorption; they help preserve bone and joint structure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromote synovial fluid production\u003C/strong\u003E - These drugs primarily target inflammation and joint damage, not synovial fluid production\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF alpha) is a cytokine involved in inflammation and the breakdown of collagen in joints.","TNF alpha antagonists are used to slow the progression of joint damage in inflammatory conditions like rheumatoid arthritis.","By inhibiting TNF alpha, these drugs help maintain joint integrity and reduce inflammation."],"references":["Padda IS, Goyal A. Leflunomide. 2023 Jun 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491731","Tian H, Cronstein BN. Understanding the mechanisms of action of methotrexate: implications for the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis. Bull NYU Hosp Jt Dis. 2007;65(3):168-73. PMID: 17922664","Waller, D. G., \u0026 Hitchings, A. W. (2021). Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book: Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tashjian, A. H., \u0026 Armstrong, E. J. (2011). Principles of pharmacology: the pathophysiologic basis of drug therapy. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. 2023 Jul 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809527","Jackson JM. TNF- alpha inhibitors. Dermatol Ther. 2007 Jul-Aug;20(4):251-64. doi: 10.1111/j.1529-8019.2007.00138.x. Erratum in: Dermatol Ther. 2008 Mar-Apr;21(2):150. PMID: 17970890"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59299"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18209"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59299"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T05:53:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T05:54:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10923"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73823"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{